The sequence length \( n \) can vary from 1 to 10. Key steps: 1. **Threshold Model**: Each element in the universal set can be considered to be added at a specific position \( t \) (from 1 to 10), meaning it is included in all subsets from \( t \) onwards. If an element is never added, it is excluded from all subsets. 2. **Independence of Elements**: Each element independently chooses a threshold \( t \) from 1 to 10. The sequence length is determined by the maximum threshold among all elements. 3. **Counting Sequences**: For each element, there are 10 choices (thresholds 1 to 10). Since there are 10 elements, the total number of sequences is \( 10^{10} \). 4. **Modulo Operation**: We need the remainder when \( 10^{10} \) is divided by 10. Since \( 10^{10} \) ends in 0, the remainder is 0. Thus, the remainder when \( K \) is divided by 10 is \(\boxed{0}\).
